{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474747"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12378"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12378"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.61,0.11,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114697"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4890"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96700"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114697"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of sudden onset shortness of breath and cough. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears agitated with marked increased work of breathing, and wheezing is audible from the end of the bed. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 47/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Pulmonary auscultation reveals bilateral wheeze and basilar crackles. The boy has been given oxygen, salbutamol, and oral prednisolone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be included in the initial treatment in addition to these measures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further treatment necessary","Ipratropium bromide","Intravenous magnesium sulfate","Adrenaline","Theophylline"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy is experiencing an acute asthma exacerbation. The severity can be assessed using tools such as the Wheezing Severity Score (WSS) as defined by the Royal Children\u0027s Hospital. His WSS is 7 (respiratory rate = 2; wheeze = 3; sternocleidomastoid use = 2) and his SpO2 is 90%. This score places him in the severe category, indicating that \u003Cstrong\u003Eipratropium bromide\u003C/strong\u003E should be added to the initial treatment regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor severe asthma exacerbations in children, the recommended initial management includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhaled salbutamol (six puffs every 20 minutes for the first hour for children under six years)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhaled ipratropium bromide (four puffs every 20 minutes for the first hour for children under six years)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral steroids (or intravenous if vomiting)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E*Note: The Australian Asthma Handbook table of initial management only refers to SABA treatment however further in the handbook it states that Ipratropium can be added on (or commenced immediately) for severe or life threatening asthma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further treatment\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate given the severity of the exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for cases where there is a poor response to initial treatment in severe acute asthma exacerbations. It is not part of the initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is generally only considered if anaphylaxis is suspected. In this case, there is no mention of a trigger or other signs of anaphylaxis such as urticaria, hypotension, or gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETheophylline\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended in the management of acute asthma due to its unfavourable side effect profile and the availability of safer, more effective alternatives.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ipratropium bromide should be added to salbutamol, oxygen, and steroids in the initial management of severe paediatric asthma exacerbations.","The Wheezing Severity Score is a useful tool for assessing the severity of asthma exacerbations in children."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital. Acute Asthma [Internet]. Melbourne; 2020 [updated 2020; cited 2023]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Asthma_Acute/","Perth Children\u0027s Hospital. Asthma [Internet]. Perth; 2021 [updated 2022 April; cited 2023 Jan 9]. Available from: https://pch.health.wa.gov.au/For-health-professionals/Emergency-Department-Guidelines/Asthma","National Asthma Council. Managing acute asthma in children 1-5 years in the ED [Internet]. Australia; 2015. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/acute-asthma/children-1-5-years/managing-acute-asthma-in-children-1-5-years-in-the-ed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96700"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96700"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T20:47:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T20:48:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4890"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114697"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0